It's hard work and the rewiring processes take time, not to mention a level of self-compassion I'm often not able to find. But every word helps, and so does every bit of support within this incomparable community of beautiful souls. ✒🖤
@thewordforthis 🖤🖤🖤🖤

#TWFT52 WEEK 23 – Swipe for starter questions and my own response (also at link in profile).
@thewordforthis
✒🖤
• 
The Word for This is “SHAME”
• 
I cannot (still, will not)
pretend I didn’t
anticipate, dress and wait
by windows in
late-morning light,
dread and delight learning
early to curl into each other, white
tights not yet unclean,
back
(behind)
to the wall, resigned to
calculate the price
for which I’d sold my
right to be my own.
• 
It was tempting to stay at the surface; I wanted to turn away, to focus on body image struggles over the years (now too, who am I kidding?), or the deep sense of failure at how body and brain are collapsing under the decades-old fire of fight/flight wiring that’s finally burning itself (and me) out, and wondering whether what’s left will have (has) any value.
• 
See? A lot in there. But.
• 
Children are sexually assaulted by family members in countless ways, and the shame of loving the person who hurt you, of having sought their love, is… I don’t have a word for it. And because the behavior was sanctioned, open, seen by all, encouraged – because I was shamed for being (over)sensitive, for not catering to his twisted needs, for having a body that didn’t deserve its own space (because it took up too much? is that possible?) – even typing “sexually assaulted” is a challenge, still. Is that the word for this?
• 
I don’t have a word for the filth of the hug I owed as thanks for this gift or that, knowing his hands would squeeze and pinch and grab, the child willing to tolerate, not only because she wanted the toy or the doll, but because she was told it was all just his form of love.
• 
Knowing contempt and anger were the only form of love I deserved.
• 
I have to forgive her, forgive me (is the opposite of shame “resilience”? the phrase needs examination). Because I’m still holding back from receiving the love that’s downstairs from me right now, no strings, no anger, no price point. Just relentlessly unconditional, and a safety that’s still too frightening to accept.

@thewordforthis thank you for your kind words. Will it ever stop?  When will the predictors be held accountable?

@mccoolth I wish I had better answers, and the broader umbrella of rape culture is so deeply ingrained that I'm *still* noticing new instances, examples, tropes, etc. But every time one of us says "no, this is not OK" - whether out loud or simply for ourselves - we're creating accountability. It matters. It *has* to matter. ✒🖤
@thewordforthis 💕

@unseen_unheard_poet Thank you, my friend. There are thousands more words to be written on this, but even just starting to push myself past the easy response feels like progress. Each prompt opens another door, and I'm trying to remember that I don't have to articulate all of it at once. I'm so grateful for you, as always. ✒🖤
@thewordforthis ❤️💔❤️😍 I’m giving you my love and sending you strength
Your response to this is so powerful and heartbreaking. The caption afterwards is so relatable and well articulated 💔🙌🏻
@rumi_brinkley You have no idea how much I needed to hear that, and how much it means to me. Then again, maybe you do. Much love to you, always. ✒🖤
You’ve helped me so much. Thank you for the support & sisterhood. It matters.

@wildflower_warriors Thank you, love. And victim-blaming is so utterly ingrained... the world around us trains us to feel shame and guilt as a baseline. It's insidious, and that's why we need to talk about it. Keep valuing yourself, my friend. You deserve to heal. ✒🖤

😭 Made my heart sink. That caption is so beautifully & powerfully written. Shame/guilt-I have carried its burden for decades. Although I was assaulted by a stranger, I was too ashamed to speak out for fear of being seen imperfect or damaged. Also I completely dissociated from the world for several months after my rape, & by the time I came back to my mind, I simply resolved to bury the pain. It took years of intensive therapy for me to finally realize that it was not my fault.
@wind_swept_beauty_of_the_wild I love this idea, and courage is an important concept in my world view. Thank you for that! ✒🖤
for me personally the opposite of shame would be courage, which also takes a whole lot of vulnerability. Thank you for sharing 🖤

But every word helps, and so does every bit of support within this incomparable community of beautiful souls. ✒🖤

Your response to this prompt is so raw and real and heart-wrenching.  You are amazing, and the healing is coming.. your strength in sharing is such brilliant evidence of that. 🖤🖤🖤 Sending so much love.
